Africa
------
[1] Namibia (Windhoek)
Date: Tue 2 Sep 2014
From: Johann van den Heever <vdheej@health.gov.za> [edited]


Urgent and more information is required from Namibian or other reliable sources to verify the extent of the current measles outbreak in Namibia. Five specimens tested IgM positive for measles. These were sent by general practitioners in Windhoek, Namibia to a private laboratory in Cape Town and were confirmed positive by the National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD) in South Africa. The patients (4 males and one female), ranging in age between 8 and 44 years old, had specimens taken on 3, 4, 6, 9, and 20 Aug 2014, respectively.

More information is required in order to inform health workers and the general public on how they can adequately protect themselves and be on the alert for suspected cases of fever, rash and one of the following: cough, conjunctivitis, and coryza.

--
Johann van den Heever
Manager
Expanded Programme on Immunisation
South Africa
<vdheej@health.gov.za>

[ProMED-mail thanks Johann van den Heever for provision of this advance warning of a measles outbreak in Namibia. Further information from any informed sources would be welcomed. - Mod.CP

A ProMED-mail HealthMap is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2755200,163.]

