[Maguindanao is a province of the Philippines located in the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao (ARMM). Its capital is Shariff Aguak. It borders Lanao del Sur to the north, Cotabato to the east, and Sultan Kudarat to the south. A map showing the location of Maguindanao can be accessed at: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maguindanao. Previously, in Measles update (35), a total of 7 fatalities and 1228 cases of measles were reported from Davao City, the largest city in Mindanao. Such figures explain the predominance of the Philippines as a source of many cases of travel-related measles throughout the world. - Mod.CP

A ProMED-mail HealthMap is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2755200,28389.]

******
[5] Solomon Islands
Date: Mon 1 Sep 2014
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/solomon-islands-measles-outbreak-tops-500-500/


The measles outbreak that started in early July [2014] in Honiara, Solomon Islands has grown to at least 550 cases, the Solomon Islands Health Ministry said recently. In a Radio New Zealand report today [1 Sep 2014], the permanent secretary of the ministry, Dr Lester Ross, says it's likely there are thousands more cases that haven't yet been reported. At least 2 children have died from complications of measles. A measles mass vaccination campaign will target all people aged from 6 months to 30 years of age, the report states. The outbreak has spread past Honiara, as cases are now being reported in Malaita, Guadalcanal, Isabel, Western province, Temotu, and Renbel.

Measles or rubeola, is an acute, highly communicable viral disease that is characterized by Koplik spots in the cheek or tongue very early in the disease. A couple of days later, a red blotchy rash appears, 1st on the face, and then spreads, lasting 4-7 days. Other symptoms include fever, cough and red watery eyes. The patient may be contagious from 4 days prior to the rash appearance to 4 days after rash appearance.

The disease is more severe in infants and adults. Complications from measles, which are reported in up to 20 percent of people infected, include seizures, pneumonia, deafness and encephalitis.

[byline: Robert Herriman]

